{"cursor":"16399","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox language |name=Vedic Sanskrit |nativename= |region= Northwestern\nIndian subcontinent |states= Bronze Age India, Iron Age India |era= Early Vedic\nperiod |ethnicity= Ärya |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=Indo-Iranian |fam3=Indo-\nAryan |iso3=vsn|iso3comment=([http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/chg_detail.asp?id=2011-\n041 proposed]) |notice=IPA }}\n\n'Vedic Sanskrit' is an Old Indo-Aryan language. It is an archaic form of\nSanskrit, an early descendant of Proto-Indo-Iranian. It is closely related to\nAvestan, the oldest preserved Iranian language. Vedic Sanskrit is the oldest\nattested language of the Indo-Iranian branch of the Indo-European family.\n\nVedic Sanskrit is the language of the Vedas, texts compiled over the period of\nearly-to-mid 2nd to mid 1st millennium BC. Vedic Sanskrit has been orally\npreserved as a part of the Årauta tradition of Vedic chanting, predating the\nadvent of alphabetic writing in India by several centuries. For lack of both\nepigraphic evidence and an unbroken manuscript tradition, Vedic Sanskrit can be\nconsidered a reconstructed language. Especially the oldest stage of the\nlanguage, 'Rigvedic Sanskrit', the language of the hymns of the Rigveda, is\npreserved only in a redacted form several centuries younger than the texts'\ncomposition. Recovering its original form is a matter of linguistic\nreconstruction. [http://www.utexas.edu/cola/centers/lrc/RV/ Restoring\nhistorical language of the vedas from attested vedic]\n\nFrom about the 6th century BC, in the classical period of Iron Age Ancient\nIndia, Vedic Sanskrit gave way to Classical Sanskrit as defined by the\ngrammar of .\n","linknr":572,"url":"Vedic_Sanskrit","recorded":1374523834,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Vedic_Sanskrit&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Vedic_Sanskrit&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creat